# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: charlotte-north-carolina
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] It is the site of the former Independence Building which was constructed in 1909, it was demolished in September 1981.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] At its opening The Independence Building with 12 floors was the tallest building in North Carolina.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The developers Faison firm and Williams Realty of Tulsa, Oklahoma announced in October 1981 the specifics of the building.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] NCNB, now Bank of America, planned to lease 260,000 square feet (24,155 m2) on floors 2 - 10.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The building was built diagonal from NCNB Plaza, the bank headquarters in 1981.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Therefore, the building was planned to be an extension of the bank's headquarters.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The building was forecasted to cost $48 million.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] NCNB planned to consolidate its corporate services from a 100,000 square feet (9,290 m2) building it purchased in 1970 and the 60,000 square feet (5,574 m2) of additional leased space into the building.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The bank moved 700 employees into the building in August 1983.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] At the time this accounted for about a third of the bank's 2,300 local employees.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Other tenants began to occupy floors 10 - 20 in September 198.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] In October 1983 Smith Barney Harris Upham & Co.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Inc., a stock brokerage, left NCNB Plaza.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Insurance broker Alexander and Alexander moved from Wachovia Center.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Later in the month Brooks Fashion opened a 2,900 square feet (269 m2) store in the building.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Wheat, First Securities Inc., a stock brokerage moved from a 5,000 square feet (465 m2) space at Northwestern building.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Fashion store The Limited opened a 3,000 square feet (279 m2) store.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] In November 1983 law firm Fleming, Robinson, Bradshaw & Hinson signed a lease for 20,000 square feet (1,858 m2) on the top two floors.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Previously the firm had leased 16,000 square feet (1,486 m2) on two floors at First Union Plaza.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] At that time the building was 70% leased.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Then later in the same month 3 new tenants signed leases to bring the building to 75% leased.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The companies include Chubb & Sons, an insurance underwriting firm, leasing 9,000 square feet on the 17th floor; Sterling Capital Management Co, an investment counseling firm, leasing 5,400 on the 17th floor; and Grier and Grier, a law firm, leased 2,200 square feet on the 2nd floor.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] In August 1996 Cousins Properties announced it had reached an agreement to purchase the building for $69.3 million.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Part of the announcement was possibility of also creating a $300 million uptown basketball and entertainment complex composed of four blocks of Uptown.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] In March 1998 building tenant Robinson, Bradshaw & Hinson announced a $1 million makeover of their current 65,000 square feet (6,039 m2) of space and the addition of 17,000 square feet (1,579 m2) of space.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] At the time of the announcement the company had 225 employees occupying the space.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] American Financial Realty Trust purchased the building in September 2004 for $100 million from Cousins Properties Inc.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Local property management company Colliers Pinkard was hired to handle leasing.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The building was 92% occupied at the time of the sale with Bank of America Corp. and the Robinson, Bradshaw & Hinson law firm as the anchor tenants.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] In June 2011 law firm Robinson Bradshaw & Hinson signed a 10-year renewal for 108,155 square feet (10,048 m2).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] At the time of signing the renewal they had 125 local employees and were the second largest law firm in Charlotte after Moore & Van Allen.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] In October 2011 Northeastern University opened its Charlotte with 14,000 square feet (1,301 m2) in the building for offices and classrooms.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The school's goal was to eventually have 2,000 enrolled in the Charlotte campus.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] LRC Properties and Cornerstone Real Estate Advisors purchased 101 Independence Center from previous owner KBS Capital Advisors and Gramercy Property Trust in 2015 for $108 million.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] At the time it was 84% occupied with Bank of America as the largest occupant with 261,000 square feet (24,248 m2).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] In August 2015 Bank of America vacated 95,000 square feet (8,826 m2) across four floors.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Accounting firm CliftonLarsonAllen vacated the tenth floor earlier in 2015 which left 119,296 square feet (11,083 m2) of continuous space available.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Few buildings in Uptown Charlotte at that time had that amount of continuous space available.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] In September 2015 Stewart Engineering signed a lease for 16,000 square feet (1,486 m2) on the 14th floor.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The company relocated their employees from BB&T Center to the space in early 2015.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] In August 2017, an $8 million building renovation began.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The renovations included adding a collobration area to the atrium, new art work in the lobby, and updated hallways and restrooms.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Also in 2017 New York-based Sunlight Financial signed a lease for 13,500 square feet (1,254 m2) in the building in November.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The company issues loans for residential solar projects.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Their 20 local employees moved from Packard Place in the first quarter of 2018.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Crescent Communities and Nuveen purchased the building in 2019 from LRC Properties for $132.3 million.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Currently Crescent is spending $25 million to renovate the building.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The renovation will mostly affect the ground floor with the overhaul of the lobby, adding additional outdoor seating, and renovation of future ground floor retail space.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The goal is to make retail more accessible from the street.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Previously most retail was accessible from the interior.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The building was 80% leased as of August 2020, its tenants included Bank of America, Robinson Bradshaw, Levvel, Northeastern University, and Sunlight Financial and Spaces.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Levvel's occupancy is part of a doubling of Charlotte office square footage from 12,000 square feet (1,115 m2) in NASCAR Plaza to 24,000 square feet (2,230 m2).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The company chose the building due to its close proximity to parking and the light rail.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] It currently has 90 employees in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] In May 2022 Robinson Bradshaw announced they will vacate their space in the building in 2024 when 600 South Tryon is complete to become the anchor tenant occupying 102,000 square feet (9,476 m2).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The firm will occupy the top 4 floors of the 24 story building that has 415,000 square feet (38,555 m2).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] This will be the fourth building in Legacy Union.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] In July 2022 Stays by Walker, a short term rental agency, announced they will be leasing 3,000 square feet (279 m2) in the building.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The company relocated from Prosperity Place in University Area.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Kay Walker, CEO of Stays Walker, stated this about the space “The proximity to so many of Charlotte's major corporate players will be a huge asset to our company, and our team members will enjoy the property's newly renovated common spaces and top-of-the-line amenities.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] In August 2022 UK based The Bank of London announced it will be leasing 40,000 square feet (3,716 m2) in the building to house the 350 jobs they're creating in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The bank currently has offices in New York and Belfast.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Positions will include software development, compliance and risk, technology operations, infrastructure engineering and business operations.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] All jobs are planned to be created by 2026.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] In October 2022 building permits revealed that a 17,290 square feet (1,606 m2) food hall will be built on the first floor of the building called Monarch Food Hall.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The food hall management company is Hospitality HQ.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The project is described on the Hospitality HQ website as having 3 bars and artisan food concepts from around the world.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] This project is part of Crescent Communities, the building owner's, $25 million renovation of the building.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The food hall will include 12 stalls, a full service restaurant occupying 4,300 square feet (399 m2), three bars including one that will be outside along North Tryon, and private event space.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] In August 2023 it was announced that a few dining options have signed on for the food hall.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] These include Barley and Burger, serving gourmet burgers; Curry Junction, a concept by the owners of Curry Gate, an Indian and Nepalese restaurant; Rolled AF, is a Mexican restaurant that is a joint operation by the owners of Nacho Average Truck and 22 Street Kitchen.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The market will include a total of 12 stalls.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] In December 2023 additional food stalls were announced.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Brooklyn Dumpling Shop, a sweet and savory dumpling shop; also Dock Local, a shop featuring seafood rolls, sandwiches, and tacos will have be available in December 2023.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Chicago-based FARE, serving grain and vegetable rolls, will be available in spring 2024.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] The recently completed $25 million renovation which included Monarch Market are contributing to an increase in occupancy.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] In February 2024 Crescent Communities announced it had signed six leases amounting to 68,600 square feet (6,373 m2) space.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/101-independence-center] Two of the companies include Genesis10, moving from the Johnston Building and Bloomreach moving from 1920 Abbott St. in South End.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] The **145th Airlift Wing** is a unit of the North Carolina Air National Guard.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] It is assigned to Charlotte Air National Guard Base, North Carolina and is equipped with the Boeing C-17 Globemaster III aircraft.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] If activated to federal service in the United States Air Force, the 145th is gained by Air Mobility Command.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] The 145th Fighter Group was constituted and allotted to the North Carolina Air National Guard, at Morris Field, North Carolina on 28 May 1957.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] Its 156th Fighter Squadron began trading their North American F-86A Sabres, for the more capable F-86E.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] The **145th Fighter Group** (Air Defense) was assigned to the 126th Air Defense Wing, Illinois Air National Guard, Chicago On 1 February 1961, the group was redesignated the **145th Aeromedical Transport Group**, and converted to Fairchild C-119 Flying Boxcars.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] The group was gained by the 1st Aeromedical Transport Group and Western Transport Air Force, Travis AFB, CA, for training and flying evacuation missions.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] It transited to Lockheed C-121 Constellation transports during 1962–1965.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] On 25 January 1964 the 145th was redesignated **145th Air Transport Group** (Heavy).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] The unit began to convert to Douglas C-124 Globemaster II transports during 1965.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] From 1966 to 1971 the 145th deployed crews and aircraft to Vietnam, flying over 20 million km without an aircraft accident.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] It was redesignated **145th Tactical Airlift Group** on 15 May 1971 and re-equipped with Lockheed C-130 Hercules transport aircraft.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] In 1990 saw the unit mobilized for Operation Desert Shield, followed by Operation Desert Storm in 1991.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] 15 Mar 1992, brought about another name change with the group becoming the **145th Airlift Group**.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] During 1993 the group started to replace their elderly C-130Bs and take delivery of the more modern C-130H3.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] On 1 Oct 1995, it was redesignated the **145th Airlift Wing**.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] On 7 September 2016 saw the end of its aerial firefighting mission using MAFFS (Modular Airborne Fire Fighting System) when it was transferred to the 152nd Airlift Wing, Nevada Air National Guard.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] There are two other C-130 Air National Guard MAFFS trained units, 153rd Airlift Wing, Wyoming Air National Guard, Cheyenne; the 146th Airlift Wing, California Air National Guard, Channel Islands, CA; and one Air Force Reserve unit, 302nd Airlift Wing, Air Force Reserve, Peterson Air Force Base, CO.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/145th-airlift-wing] The wing's last C-130 departed on 22 December 2017 before the wing received its first C-17 Globemaster III on Saturday 7 April 2018.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The **1880 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office during June 1880, was the tenth United States census.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] It was the first time that women were permitted to be enumerators.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The Superintendent of the Census was Francis Amasa Walker.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York City—recorded a population of over one million, and the first census in which the 20 most populated cities all recorded over 100,000 residents.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] Schedule 4 (Social statistics) was the responsibility of experts and special agents, rather than the enumerators.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The majority of the data came from correspondence with officials of institutions providing care and treatment of certain members of the population.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] Experts and special agents also were employed to collect data on valuation, taxation, and indebtedness; religion and libraries; colleges, academies, and schools; newspapers and periodicals, and wages.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1880 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series, which contains microdata.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau; after which the original sheets were transferred to various state archives, libraries, or universities.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is available in rolls from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along which digital indices.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1880 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census determined the resident population of the United States to be 50,189,209, an increase of 30.2 percent over the 38,555,983 persons enumerated during the 1870 census.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The mean center of United States population for 1880 was in Boone County, Kentucky.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The results from the census were used to determine the apportionment for the 48th, 49th, 50th, 51st, and 52nd sessions of the United States Congress.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The processing of the 1880 census data took so long (eight years) that the Census Bureau contracted Herman Hollerith to design and build a tabulating machine to be used for the next census.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census also led to the discovery of the Alabama paradox.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Between 2004 and 2014, Charlotte was among the country's fastest-growing metropolitan areas, with 888,000 new residents.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Based on U.S. census data from 2005 to 2015, Charlotte tops the U.S. in millennial population growth.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Throughout the 2020s, it has remained one of the fastest-growing major cities in the United States.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Residents of Charlotte are referred to as "Charlotteans".
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte is home to the corporate headquarters of Bank of America, Honeywell, Truist Financial, and the East Coast headquarters of Wells Fargo, which, when combined with other Charlotte-based financial institutions, makes the city the second-largest banking center in the nation.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte's notable attractions include three professional sports teams, the Carolina Panthers of the NFL, the Charlotte Hornets of the NBA, and Charlotte FC of MLS.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The city is also home to the NASCAR Hall of Fame, Opera Carolina, Charlotte Symphony, Charlotte Ballet, Children's Theatre of Charlotte, Mint Museum, Harvey B.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Gantt Center, Bechtler Museum of Modern Art, the Billy Graham Library, Levine Museum of the New South, Charlotte Museum of History, Carowinds amusement park, and U.S.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte has a humid subtropical climate.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] It is located several miles east of the Catawba River and southeast of Lake Norman, the largest human-made lake in North Carolina.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Lake Wylie and Mountain Island Lake are two smaller human-made lakes located near the city.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] As of 2024, 66% of the city's area is occupied by green spaces.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The city ranks as the greenest in North America and 28th in the world.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Catawba Indians are the earliest known inhabitants of the Charlotte area.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] They were first encountered in the region in 1567 by the Spanish Conquistador Juan Pardo.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The area that is now Charlotte was first settled by European colonists around 1755 when Thomas Spratt and his family settled near what is now the Elizabeth neighborhood.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Thomas Polk (great-uncle of President James K.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Polk), who later married Thomas Spratt's daughter, built his house by the intersection of two Native American trading paths between the Yadkin and Catawba rivers.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] One path ran north–south and was part of the Great Wagon Road; the second path ran east–west along what is now Trade Street.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] By 1759, half the Catawba tribe had died from smallpox, an endemic disease among European colonists, against which the Catawba had no natural immunity.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] At its peak, the Catawba population was 10,000.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] But by 1826, the Catawba population dropped to 110.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The city of Charlotte was developed first by a wave of migration of Scots-Irish Presbyterians, or Ulster-Scot settlers from Ulster, who dominated the culture of the Southern Piedmont Region and made up the principal founding population in the backcountry.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] German immigrants also settled in the area before the American Revolutionary War, but in smaller numbers.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] They still contributed greatly to the early foundations of the region.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Mecklenburg County was initially part of Bath County (1696 to 1729) of the New Hanover Precinct, which became New Hanover County in 1729.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The western portion of New Hanover split into Bladen County in 1734, and its western portion split into Anson County in 1750.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Mecklenburg County was formed from Anson County in 1762.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Further apportionment was made in 1792, after the American Revolutionary War, with Cabarrus County formed from Mecklenburg.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Nicknamed the "Queen City", like its county a few years earlier, Charlotte was named in honor of Charlotte of Mecklenburg-Strelitz, who had become the queen consort of Great Britain and Ireland in 1761, seven years before the town's incorporation.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] A second nickname derives from the American Revolutionary War, when British commander General Charles Cornwallis, 1st Marquess Cornwallis occupied the city but was driven out by hostile residents.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] He wrote that Charlotte was "a hornet's nest of rebellion", leading to the historical nickname "The Hornet's Nest".
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Within decades of Polk's settling, the area grew to become the Town of Charlotte, incorporated in 1768.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Though chartered as Charlotte, the name appears as a form of "Charlottesburgh" on many maps until around 1800.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] A form of "Charlottetown" also appears on maps of British origin depicting General Cornwallis' route of invasion.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The crossroads in Piedmont became the heart of Uptown Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In 1770, surveyors marked the streets in a grid pattern for future development.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The east–west trading path became Trade Street, and the Great Wagon Road became Tryon Street, in honor of William Tryon, a royal governor of colonial North Carolina.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The intersection of Trade and Tryon is commonly known today as "Trade and Tryon", or simply "The Square", and formally as "Independence Square".
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] While surveying the boundary between the Carolinas in 1772, William Moultrie stopped in Charlotte, whose five or six houses were "very ordinary built of logs".
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Local leaders came together in 1775 and signed the Mecklenburg Resolves, more popularly known as the Mecklenburg Declaration of Independence.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] While not a true declaration of independence from British rule, it is among the first such declarations that eventually led to the American Revolution.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] May 20, the traditional date of the signing of the declaration, is celebrated annually in Charlotte as "MecDec", with musket and cannon fire by reenactors in Independence Square.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] North Carolina's state flag and state seal also bear the date.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In 1799, in nearby Cabarrus County, 12-year-old Conrad Reed found a 17- pound rock, which his family used as a doorstop.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Three years later, a jeweler determined it was nearly solid gold, paying the family a paltry $3.50.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The first documented gold find in the United States of any consequence set off the nation's first gold rush.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Many veins of gold were found in the area throughout the 19th and early 20th centuries, leading to the 1837 founding of the Charlotte Mint.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] North Carolina was the chief producer of gold in the United States, until the Sierra Nevada was found in 1848, although the volume mined in the Charlotte area was dwarfed by subsequent rushes.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In 1842, Union County formed from Mecklenburg's southeastern portion and a western portion of Anson County.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] These areas were all part of one of the original six judicial/military districts of North Carolina known as the Salisbury District.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte is traditionally considered the home of Southern Presbyterianism, but in the 19th century, numerous churches, including Presbyterian, Baptist, Methodist, Episcopal, Lutheran, and Roman Catholic formed, eventually giving Charlotte the nickname, "The City of Churches".
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Some groups still pan for gold occasionally in local streams and creeks.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Charlotte Mint was active until 1861 when Confederate forces seized it at the outbreak of the Civil War.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The mint was not reopened at the war's end, but the building, albeit in a different location, now houses the Mint Museum of Art.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The city's first boom came after the Civil War, as Charlotte became a cotton processing center and railroad hub.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] By the 1880s, Charlotte sat astride the Southern Railway mainline from Atlanta to Washington, D.C.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Farmers from miles around would bring cotton to the railroad platform in Uptown.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Local promotors began building textile factories, starting with the 1881 Charlotte Cotton Mill that still stands at Graham and 5th streets.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte's city population at the 1890 census grew to 11,557.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In 1910, Charlotte surpassed Wilmington to become North Carolina's largest city with 34,014 residents.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The population grew again during World War I, when the U.S. government established Camp Greene, north of present-day Wilkinson Boulevard.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The camp supported 40,000 soldiers, with many troops and suppliers staying after the war, launching urbanization that eventually overtook older cities along the Piedmont Crescent.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In the 1920 census, Charlotte fell to being the state's second largest city, Winston-Salem with 48,395 people, had two thousand more people than Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte would pass Winston-Salem in population by the 1930 census, and has remained North Carolina's largest city since.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Until 1958, the Seaboard Air Line Railroad operated a daily passenger train from its own station (which had opened in 1896) to Wilmington.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The city's modern-day banking industry achieved prominence in the 1970s and 1980s, largely under the leadership of financier Hugh McColl.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] McColl transformed North Carolina National Bank (NCNB) into a formidable national bank that through aggressive acquisitions eventually merged with BankAmerica to become Bank of America.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] First Union, later Wachovia in 2001, experienced similar growth before it was acquired by San Francisco–based Wells Fargo in 2008.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Measured by control of assets, Charlotte became the second largest banking headquarters in the United States after New York City.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] On September 22, 1989, the city was hit by Hurricane Hugo.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] With sustained winds of 69 mph (111 km/h) and gusts of 87 mph (140 km/h), Hugo caused massive property damage, destroyed 80,000 trees, and knocked out electrical power to most of the population.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Residents were without power for weeks, schools were closed for a week or more, and the cleanup took months.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The city was caught unprepared; Charlotte is 200 miles (320 km) inland, and residents from coastal areas in both Carolinas often wait out hurricanes in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In December 2002, Charlotte and much of central North Carolina were hit by an ice storm that resulted in more than 1.3 million people losing power.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] During an abnormally cold December, many were without power for weeks.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Many of the city's Bradford pear trees split apart under the weight of the ice.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In August 2015 and September 2016, the city experienced several days of protests related to the police shootings of Jonathan Ferrell and Keith Scott.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 312.00 square miles (808.1 km2), of which 310.02 square miles (802.9 km2) is land and 1.98 square miles (5.1 km2) (0.63%) is water.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte is the twenty-sixth-most expansive city in the United States and lies at an elevation of 751 feet (229 m).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte constitutes most of Mecklenburg County in the Carolina Piedmont.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Uptown Charlotte sits atop a long rise between two creeks, Sugar Creek and Irwin Creek, and was built on the gunnies of the St.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte is 25 miles (40 km) southwest of Concord; 26 miles (42 km) northeast of Rock Hill, South Carolina; 83 miles (134 km) southwest of Greensboro; 135 miles (217 km) west of Fayetteville; and 165 miles (266 km) southwest of Raleigh, the state capital.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Though the Catawba River and its lakes lie several miles west, there are no significant bodies of water or other geological features near the city center.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Consequently, development has neither been constrained nor helped by waterways or ports that have contributed to many cities of similar size.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The lack of these obstructions has contributed to Charlotte's growth as a highway, rail, and air transportation hub.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte has 199 neighborhoods radiating in all directions from Uptown.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Biddleville, the primary historic center of Charlotte's African American community, is west of Uptown, starting at the Johnson C.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Smith University campus and extending to the airport.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] East of The Plaza and north of Central Avenue, Plaza Midwood is known for its international population, including Eastern Europeans, Greeks, Middle-Easterners, and Hispanics.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] North Tryon and the Sugar Creek area include several Asian American communities.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] NoDa (North Davidson), north of Uptown, is an emerging center for arts and entertainment.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Myers Park, Dilworth, and Eastover are home to some of Charlotte's most affluent, oldest and largest houses, on tree-lined boulevards, with Freedom Park nearby.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The SouthPark area offers shopping, dining, and multifamily housing.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Far South Boulevard is home to a large Hispanic community.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Many students, researchers, and affiliated professionals live near UNC Charlotte in the northeast area known as University City.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The large area known as Southeast Charlotte is home to many golf communities, luxury developments, churches, the Jewish community center, and private schools.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] As undeveloped land within Mecklenburg has become scarce, many of these communities have expanded into Weddington and Waxhaw in Union County.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Ballantyne, in the south of Charlotte, and nearly every area on the I‑485 perimeter, has experienced rapid growth over the past ten years.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Steele Creek neighborhood which is primarily in Mecklenburg county is located in Southwest Charlotte and is known for its outdoor recreation and shopping opportunities.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Since the 1980s in particular, Uptown Charlotte has undergone massive construction of buildings, housing Bank of America, Wells Fargo, Hearst Corporation, and Duke Energy, several hotels, and multiple condominium developments.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Latta Park was created in 1891 as an amusement park.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Bryant Park was established in the 1930s and is one of the earliest small-scale public parks in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] It is the only green space remaining in West Morehead Street's industrial sector.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The 120-acre (49 ha) Park Road Park is a prominent landmark near the SouthPark area.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Park Road Park features eight basketball courts, two horseshoe pits, six baseball fields, five picnic shelters, volleyball courts, playgrounds, trails, tennis courts, and an 11-acre (4.5 ha) lake.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Charlotte-Mecklenburg Parks & Recreation Department operates 36 tennis facilities and the 12 lighted tennis courts at the park.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In September 2013, the 5.4-acre (2.2 ha) Romare Bearden Park opened to the public.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The urban section of Little Sugar Creek Greenway was completed in 2012.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Inspired in part by the San Antonio River Walk, and integral to Charlotte's extensive urban park system, it is "a huge milestone" according to Gwen Cook, greenway planner for Mecklenburg County Park and Recreation.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] However, the Little Sugar Creek Greenway bears no relation to the San Antonio River Walk.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The city of Charlotte and Mecklenburg County began purchasing flood-prone homes in the 1990s.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Voluntary buyouts of 700 households have created around 200 acres (81 ha)s of open land that can flood safely, thereby saving an estimated $28 million in flood damage and emergency rescues.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] McAlpine Creek Park and integrated McAlpine Creek Greenway constructed in 1978 was the first greenway built in the western piedmont of North Carolina.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Like much of the Piedmont region of the southeastern United States, Charlotte has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen *Cfa*), with four distinct seasons.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte is part of USDA hardiness zone 8a, transitioning to 7b in the suburbs in all directions except the south.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Winters are short and fairly mild, with a normal January daily high temperature of 52.3 °F (11.3 °C) and daily mean temperature of 42.1 °F (5.6 °C).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] On occasion temperatures can fall below 20 °F (−6.7 °C), but Charlotte also enjoys multiple warm winter days with highs in excess of 65 °F (18.3 °C).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] On average, there are 59 nights per year that drop to or below freezing, and only 1.5 days that fail to rise above freezing.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Summers are hot and humid, with a normal July daily high temperature of 90.3 °F (32.4 °C) and daily mean temperature of 80.1 °F (26.7 °C).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Hot and humid days can arrive as early as May and last until the end of September.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] There is an average of 44 days per year with highs at or above 90 °F (32 °C).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Official record temperatures range from 104 °F (40 °C) recorded six times on 6 September 1954, 9–10 August 2007 and June 29 to July 1, 2012, down to −5 °F (−21 °C) recorded on December 30, 1880, February 14, 1899 and January 21, 1985.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The record cold daily maximum is 14 °F (−10 °C) on February 12 and 13, 1899.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The record warm daily minimum is 82 °F (28 °C) on August 13, 1881.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The average window for freezing temperatures is November 5 to March 30, allowing a growing season of 220 days.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte is directly in the path of subtropical moisture from the Gulf of Mexico as it heads up the eastern seaboard, thus the city receives ample precipitation throughout the year but also many clear, sunny days.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Precipitation is generally slightly less frequent in autumn than in spring.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] On average, Charlotte receives 43.60 inches (1,110 mm) of precipitation annually, evenly distributed throughout the year.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] There is an average of 3.5 inches (8.9 cm) of snow, mainly in January and February and rarely December or March, with more frequent ice storms and sleet mixed in with rain.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Seasonal snowfall has historically ranged from no snowfall in 2022-23 and 2023-24 to 22.6 in (57 cm) in 1959–60.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Snow and ice storms can have a major impact on the area, as they often pull tree limbs down onto power lines and make driving hazardous.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Snow has been recorded a small number of times in April, most recently on April 2, 2019.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] As of 2020, the Charlotte metropolitan area as a whole is noted for having one of the worst weather radar gaps among any major U.S.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] East Coast city, with little to no coverage in a roughly quadrilateral area spanning Concord, Salisbury and much of Statesville.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] As the nearest NWS-owned NEXRAD is located in Greer, South Carolina, more than 80 mi (130 km) to the west-southwest of Charlotte, this deficit is particularly problematic during severe thunderstorm or tornado episodes.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In the 2020 census, there were 874,579 people, 342,448 households, and 195,614 families living in the city.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Census Bureau estimates showed 885,708 residents living within Charlotte's city limits and 1,093,901 in Mecklenburg County.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The combined statistical area, or trade area, of Charlotte–Concord–Gastonia, NC–SC had an estimated population of 3,387,115 in 2023.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Figures from the more comprehensive 2010 census show Charlotte's population density was 2,457 per square mile (949/km2).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] There were 319,918 housing units at an average density of 1,074.6 per square mile (414.9/km2).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Census Bureau reported Charlotte's population as 30.2% Black and 68.9% White.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In 2020, 39.72% of the population was non-Hispanic white, 32.5% Black or African American, 0.25% Native American, 7.02% Asian, 0.05% Pacific Islander, 4.15% other or mixed, and 16.32% Hispanic or Latin American of any race.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] This reflected the national demographic shift as Hispanic or Latinos and Asians increased in population.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In 2020, the median income for a household in Charlotte was $48,670.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The median income for a family was $59,452.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Males had a median income of $38,767 versus $29,218 for females.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The per capita income for Charlotte was $29,825.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The percentage of the population living at or below the poverty line was 10.6%, with 7.8% of families living at or below the poverty line.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Out of the total population, 13.8% of those under the age of 18 and 9.7% of those 65 and older were living below the poverty line.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte has been historically Protestant and remains predominantly Protestant today.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] It is the birthplace of Billy Graham, and is also the historic seat of Southern Presbyterianism.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The changing demographics of the city's increasing population have brought scores of new denominations and faiths.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Billy Graham Evangelistic Association, Wycliffe Bible Translators' JAARS Center, SIM Missions Organization, and The Christian Research Institute make their homes in the Charlotte general area.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In 2018, Charlotte proper had over 700 places of worship.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] As of 2013, 51.91% of people in Charlotte practice religion on a regular basis, making it the second most religious city in North Carolina after Winston-Salem.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The largest religion in Charlotte is Christianity, with Baptists (13.26%) having the largest number of adherents.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The second largest Christian group are the Roman Catholics (9.43%), followed by Methodists (8.02%) and Presbyterians (5.25%).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Other Christian affiliates include Pentecostals (2.50%), Lutherans (1.30%), Episcopalians (1.20%), Latter-Day Saints (0.84%), and other Christian (8.87%) churches, including the Eastern Orthodox and non-denominational congregations.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Judaism (0.57%) is the second largest religion after Christianity, followed by Eastern religions (0.34%) and Islam (0.32%).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] According to the Pew Research Center, 73% of adults in the Charlotte Metro area identified as Christians in 2023–24.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The four largest Christian denominations are Evangelical Protestants (33%), Mainline Protestants (15%), Historically Black Protestants (15%) and Catholics (7%).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Within the Evangelical Protestants, the largest grouping are the Baptists.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Baptist Peace Fellowship of North America is headquartered in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The largest Protestant church in Charlotte, by attendance, is Elevation Church, a Southern Baptist church founded by lead pastor Steven Furtick.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The church has over 15,000 congregants at nine Charlotte locations.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Most African Americans in Charlotte are Baptists affiliated with the National Baptist Convention, the largest predominantly African American denomination in the United States.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] African American Methodists are largely affiliated with either the African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church, headquartered in Charlotte, or the African Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] African American Pentecostals are represented by several organizations such as the United House of Prayer for All People, Church of God in Christ, and the United Holy Church of America.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Presbyterian Church (USA) (Mainline Protestant) is now the fourth largest denomination in Charlotte, with 68,000 members and 206 congregations.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The second largest Presbyterian denomination, the Presbyterian Church in America (Evangelical Protestants) has 43 churches and 12,000 members, followed by the Associate Reformed Presbyterian Church (Evangelical Protestants) with 63 churches and 9,500 members.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Advent Christian Church is headquartered in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Western North Carolina Annual Conference of the United Methodist Church is also headquartered in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Both Reformed Theological Seminary and Gordon-Conwell Theological Seminary have campuses there; more recently, the religious studies academic departments of Charlotte's local colleges and universities have also grown considerably.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Roman Catholic Diocese of Charlotte was formally established in 1972.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] It covers the 46 counties in the western half of North Carolina, with more than 565,000 Catholics including an array of peoples, rites and languages.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] It operates 93 parishes and missions, 20 schools, and more than 50 ministries and programs.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Metro Charlotte is home to around 120,000 Catholics making it the third largest Christian denomination.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte's Cathedral of Saint Patrick is the seat of Bishop of Charlotte Michael T.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Matthew Parish, located in the Ballantyne neighborhood, is the largest Catholic parish with over 30,000 parishioners.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Peter's Catholic Church (Charlotte, North Carolina), located in Uptown Charlotte is the oldest Catholic church in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] It was established in 1851 and until 1940 was the only Catholic church in the city.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Greek Orthodox Church's cathedral for North Carolina, Holy Trinity Cathedral, is located in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte has the largest Jewish population in the Carolinas.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Shalom Park in south Charlotte is the hub of the Jewish community, featuring two synagogues, Temple Israel and Temple Beth El, as well as a community center, the Charlotte Jewish Day School for grades K–5, and the headquarters of the *Charlotte Jewish News*.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte is the second-largest banking center in the United States, after New York City.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Bank of America, the second-largest financial institution by total assets in the United States, is headquartered in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] It is also home to Truist Financial, the nation's sixth-largest financial institution.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Other large companies, such as Microsoft and Centene Corporation, operate their East Coast headquarters in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In November 2018, Honeywell moved its corporate headquarters to Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In June 2019, Lowe's announced it will be building its Lowe's Global Technology Center worth $153 million, which was completed in 2021 and headquarters in the South End neighborhood in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In 2019, Dole Food Company relocated its headquarters to Charlotte from California, and expanded its presence in Charlotte with its merger with Ireland-based Total Produce in February 2021.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] On May 25, 2021, it was announced that Charlotte would become the East Coast headquarters of Credit Karma.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] On September 20, 2022, the Atlantic Coast Conference (ACC) announced it will be relocating its headquarters from nearby Greensboro to Charlotte in 2023.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] On July 12, 2023, railcar company TTX announced it will move its corporate headquarters to Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Following its 2024 merger with Cedar Fair, the amusement park company Six Flags moved its corporate headquarters to Charlotte, five miles northeast of its Carowinds theme park.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] As of 2019, Charlotte has seven Fortune 500 companies in its metropolitan area, including, in order of their rank: Bank of America, Honeywell, Nucor, Lowe's, Duke Energy, Sonic Automotive, and Brighthouse Financial.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte is the major center of the U.S. motorsports industry, housing the US's only Formula One team, Haas F1, multiple teams and offices of NASCAR, the NASCAR Hall of Fame, and Charlotte Motor Speedway in Concord.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Approximately 75% of the NASCAR industry's race teams, employees and drivers are based nearby.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The large presence of the racing technology industry and the newly built NHRA dragstrip, zMAX Dragway at Concord, are influencing other top professional drag racers to move their shops to Charlotte as well.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Located in the western part of Mecklenburg County is the U.S.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] National Whitewater Center, which consists of human-made rapids of varying degrees, and is open to the public year-round.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Charlotte Region has a major base of energy-oriented organizations and has become known as "Charlotte USA – The New Energy Capital".
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In the region there are more than 240 companies directly tied to the energy sector, collectively employing more than 26,400.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Since 2007 more than 4,000 energy sector jobs have been announced.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Major energy players in Charlotte include AREVA, Duke Energy, Electric Power Research Institute, Fluor, Metso Power, Piedmont Natural Gas, Albemarle Corp, Siemens Energy, Shaw Group, Toshiba, URS Corp., and Westinghouse.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The University of North Carolina at Charlotte has a reputation in energy education and research, and its Energy Production and Infrastructure Center (EPIC) trains energy engineers and conducts research.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Over the last couple of years, Charlotte has become a tech hub, with the growth of its information technology industry.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The area is an increasingly growing trucking and freight transportation hub for the East Coast.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] There are a couple of reasons for this growth.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] First, Charlotte's close proximity to major Interstates 40, 85, 77 or 95.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Second, geographically it is also positioned within a 650-mile drive to 53% of the US population.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] A number of Charlotte-based logistics companies have experienced a lot of recent growth.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] There are few notable expansions in the last ten years that have helped to create Charlotte as a logistics hub.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In December 2015 FedEx announced plans to build a number of warehouse buildings in a Concord, North Carolina business park to locate 800 jobs there.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In August 2016 Red Classic, Coke Consolidated transportation subsidiary, announced they would be hiring for an additional 300 jobs between August 2016 and the end of 2017.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The company as of August 2022 has 357 local employees.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In October 2022 XPO, Inc. has spun off RXO into a separate company that is a truckload brokerage.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The new company has 750 local employees and $4.7 billion in annual revenue Also in October 2022 Armstrong Transport Group formerly located in the University area after relocating to South End would be adding 100 jobs to its current local headcount of 125.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Numerous residential units continue to be built uptown, including over 20 skyscrapers under construction, recently completed, or in the planning stage.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Many new restaurants, bars and clubs now operate in the Uptown area.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Several projects are transforming the Midtown Charlotte and Elizabeth area.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Population increases has also brought about gentrification in the city, particularly in predominantly African-American neighborhoods such as Biddleville and Cherry.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte was listed as the 20th largest city in the US, and the 60th fastest growing city in the US between 2000 and 2008.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Charlotte region is home to many annual festivals and special events.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Carolina Renaissance Festival operates on Saturdays and Sundays each October and November.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Located near the intersection of NC 73 and Poplar Tent Road, the Carolina Renaissance Festival is one of the largest renaissance themed events in the country.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] It features 11 stages of outdoor variety entertainment, a 22-acre village marketplace, an interactive circus, an arts and crafts fair, a jousting tournament, and a feast, all rolled into one non-stop, day-long family adventure.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Yiasou Greek Festival is a Greek Festival.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] It began in 1978 and since then has become one of Charlotte's largest cultural events.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Yiasou (the Greek word for Hello, Goodbye and Cheers) Greek Festival features Hellenic cultural exhibits, authentic Greek cuisine and homemade pastries, entertainment, live music and dancing, wine tastings, art, shopping and more.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Taste of Charlotte is a three-day festival offering samples from area restaurants, live entertainment and children's activities.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Located on Tryon Street, Taste of Charlotte spans six city blocks from Stonewall to 5th Street.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Moo and Brew Fest is an annual craft beer and burger festival that is the largest in North Carolina, held each April and includes various national musical acts.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Breakaway Music Festival is a music festival which takes place at the NC Music Factory and consists of hip hop and electronic music artists and DJs.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Heroes Convention is an annual comic book convention held in June at the Charlotte Convention Center.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Founded in 1982, it is one of the oldest and largest independent comic book conventions in the United States.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte Pride is an annual LGBT event held in August.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] In 2019, the event attracted 200,000 people to Uptown Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The event's parade became Charlotte's largest annual parade in 2017.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte Turkey Trot is an annual 5k & 8k running marathon hosted every Thanksgiving, it is also the largest running event in the state of North Carolina.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte also has the Charlotte Regional Farmers Market where local farmers sell their produce.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Three annual arts and cultural festivals celebrating visual and performing arts are hosted throughout the Charlotte region: BOOM Charlotte hosted in the Camp North End area, the Charlotte International Arts Festival hosted in Ballantyne, and Charlotte SHOUT! hosted in Uptown.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte is "... the largest metropolitan area in the United States without a zoo".
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Charlotte Zoo initiative is a proposal to allocate 250 acres (101 ha) of natural North Carolina land to be dedicated to the zoological foundation, which was incorporated in 2008.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] On August 18, 2012, Channel 14 News says that the initiative is "... still a few years away" and the plot of land is "... just seven miles from the center of uptown".
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] Charlotte is also served by the Sea Life Charlotte-Concord Aquarium in the nearby city of Concord.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The aquarium is 30,000 square feet in size, and is part of the Concord Mills mall.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The aquarium opened on February 20, 2014.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Charlotte Mecklenburg Library serves the Charlotte area with a large collection (more than 1.5 million) of books, CDs and DVDs at 15 locations in the city of Charlotte, with branches in the surrounding towns of Matthews, Mint Hill, Huntersville, Cornelius and Davidson.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] All locations provide free access to Internet-enabled computers and WiFi, and a library card from one location is accepted at all 20 locations.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The philanthropist Andrew Carnegie donated $25,000 for a library building, on the condition that the city of Charlotte donate a site and $2,500 per year for books and salaries, and that the state grant a charter for the library.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] All conditions were met, and the Charlotte Carnegie Library opened in an imposing classical building on July 2, 1903.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The 1903 state charter also required that a library be opened for the disenfranchised African-American population of Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] This was completed in 1905 with the opening of the *Brevard Street Library for Negroes*, an independent library in Brooklyn, a historically black area of Charlotte, on the corner of Brevard and East Second Streets (now Martin Luther King Boulevard).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p01] The Brevard Street Library was the first library for African Americans in the state of North Carolina, and some sources say in the southeast.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte is home to the Carolina Panthers of the National Football League (NFL), the Charlotte Hornets of the National Basketball Association (NBA), Charlotte FC of Major League Soccer (MLS) and the Carolina Chaos of the Premier Lacrosse League.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The Panthers have been located in Charlotte since the team's creation in 1995, and the current Hornets franchise has been located in Charlotte since its creation in 1988 (with the exception of the 2002-03 and 2003-04 seasons).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The Panthers and Charlotte FC play their home games in Bank of America Stadium, while the Hornets play in the Spectrum Center.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Carolina has reached the Super Bowl twice but has been unsuccessful in both losing to the New England Patriots in Super Bowl XXXVIII in 2004 and against the Denver Broncos in Super Bowl 50 in 2016.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The original Hornets NBA franchise was established in 1988 as an expansion team, but it relocated to New Orleans, Louisiana in 2002 after animosity grew between the team's fans and principal owner George Shinn.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The NBA quickly granted Charlotte an expansion franchise following the departure of the Hornets and the new franchise, the Charlotte Bobcats, began to play in 2004.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The team retook the Hornets name when the New Orleans–based team renamed itself the New Orleans Pelicans in 2013.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The name change became official on May 20, 2014.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] On the same day, the franchise reclaimed the history and records of the original 1988–2002 Hornets.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] MLS awarded its expansion team to Charlotte in 2019, which began play as Charlotte FC in 2022.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte is represented in professional ice hockey by the Charlotte Checkers and in professional baseball at the Triple-A level by the Charlotte Knights.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Since 1999, the Knights has been the Triple-A Affiliate of the Chicago White Sox.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The Charlotte Independence are a minor professional soccer club who play in USL League One the third tier of US professional soccer.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The city is also the home of the National Junior College Athletic Association (NJCAA) headquarters.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The NJCAA is the second-largest national intercollegiate athletic organization in the United States, with over 500 member schools in 43 states.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The Big South Conference is also headquartered in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Founded in 1983, the Big South Conference has 11 member institutions with over 19 different sports and completes in the NCAA's Division I.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The Atlantic Coast Conference (ACC) also has its headquarters in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Founded in 1954, the ACC has 15 member institutions 4 of whom are located in the state of North Carolina with over 28 different sports and competes in NCAA's Division I.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Over the years, Charlotte has hosted many international, collegiate, and professional sporting events.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] In professional basketball, the city hosted the NBA All-Star Game twice in 1991 at the old Charlotte Coliseum and most recently in 2019 at Spectrum Center.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] In collegiate sports, Charlotte hosts the ACC Championship Game and Duke's Mayo Bowl.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The city has also been the host many ACC men's basketball tournaments most recently in 2019.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] In 2021, Charlotte hosted the ACC baseball tournament.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] In 2017, Charlotte hosted the PGA Championship at the Quail Hollow Club and is set to host again by 2025.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte will also host the 2022 Presidents Cup.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] In 1994, Charlotte hosted the Final Four.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The Queen's Cup Steeplechase was held here since 1995–2023.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The Queen's City Polo Cup is scheduled to replace this event in 2026.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Since 1931, Jim Crockett Promotions has been a full-fledged professional wrestling performer, based in the North Carolina, South Carolina, and Virginia states, and has been called Mid-Atlantic Wrestling.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] National Wrestling Alliance, World Championship Wrestling, WWE has big matches, and many pay-per-view event.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte has participated in 11 NCAA men's basketball tournaments, 14 NCAA men's soccer tournaments, and the football team participated in their first bowl game in 2019 just six years after starting their program.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Smith University participates at the NCAA Division II level.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Johnson and Wales University participate in the USCAA.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte has a council–manager form of government.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The mayor and Charlotte City Council are elected every two years, with no term limits.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The mayor is *ex officio* chair of the City Council, and only votes in case of a tie.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Unlike other mayors in council–manager systems, Charlotte's mayor has the power to veto ordinances passed by the council; the council can override a mayoral veto by a vote of seven of its ten members.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The Council appoints a city manager to serve as chief administrative officer.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Unlike some other cities and towns in North Carolina, elections are held on a partisan basis.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Vi Lyles, a Democrat elected in 2017, became the 59th mayor of Charlotte, North Carolina.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] She was elected to her third term in 2022.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Patrick Cannon, a Democrat, was sworn in as mayor on December 2, 2013.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] On March 26, 2014, Cannon was arrested on public corruption charges.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Later the same day, he resigned as mayor.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Mayor Pro Tem Michael Barnes served as Acting Mayor until April 7, when the City Council selected State Senator Dan Clodfelter, also a Democrat, to serve the remainder of Cannon's term.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Former Mecklenburg County Commission chairwoman Jennifer Roberts defeated Clodfelter in the 2015 Democratic primary and went on to win the general election, becoming the first Democratic woman to be elected to the post.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] She was ousted in the 2017 Democratic primary by Mayor Pro Tem Vi Lyles, who later defeated Republican City Councilman Kenny Smith in the general election to become Mayor of Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Historically, voters have been friendly to moderates of both parties.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] However, in recent years, Charlotte has swung heavily to the Democrats.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Republican strength is concentrated in the southeastern portion of the city, while Democratic strength is concentrated in the south-central, eastern, and northern areas.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The city had a Republican mayor from 1987 to 2009.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The Charlotte City Council has 11 members (7 from districts and 4 at-large).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Democrats control the council with a 9-to-2 advantage, winning all 4 of the at-large seats in the November 2013, 2015, and 2017 municipal elections.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] While the City Council is responsible for passing ordinances, the city's budget, and other policies, all decisions can be overridden by the North Carolina General Assembly, since North Carolina municipalities do not have home rule.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] While municipal powers have been broadly construed since the 1960s, the General Assembly still retains considerable authority over local matters.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte is split between three congressional districts on the federal level the 8th district, represented by Republican Mark Harris, the 12th district, represented by Democrat Alma Adams, and the 14th district, represented by Republican Tim Moore.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte is represented by ten members of the North Carolina House of Representatives, Mary Gardner Belk (D-88th), Terry M.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] (D-92nd), Nasif Majeed (D-99th), John Autry (D-100th), Carolyn Logan (D-101st), Becky Carney (D-102nd), Brandon Lofton (D-104th), Wesley Harris (D-105th), Carla Cunningham (D-106th), and Kelly Alexander (D-107th), and six members of the North Carolina Senate, Mujtaba A.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Mohammed (D-38th), DeAndrea Salvador (D-39th), Joyce Waddell (D-40th), Rachel Hunt (D-42nd), Vickie Sawyer (R-37th), and Natasha Marcus (D-41st).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte was selected in 2011 to host the 2012 Democratic National Convention, which was held at the Spectrum Center.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] It began September 4, 2012, and ended on September 6, 2012.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] In 2018, Charlotte was chosen to host the Republican National Convention in August 2020.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States most events were not held in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The city's public school system, Charlotte-Mecklenburg Schools, is the second largest in North Carolina and 17th largest in the nation.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] In 2009, it won the NAEP Awards, the Nation's Report Card for urban school systems with top honors among 18 city systems for fourth grade math, second place among eighth graders.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] An estimated 144,000 students are taught in 164 separate elementary, middle, and high schools.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte is home to a number of universities and colleges such as Central Piedmont Community College, Johnson C.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Smith University, Johnson & Wales University, Queens University of Charlotte, and the University of North Carolina at Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Several notable colleges are located in the metropolitan suburbs.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Located in nearby Davidson, North Carolina is Davidson College.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Additional colleges in the area include Belmont Abbey College in the suburb of Belmont, North Carolina, Gaston College with its main campus in the suburb of Dallas, North Carolina and Wingate University in the suburb of Wingate, North Carolina.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Also nearby are Winthrop University, Clinton Junior College, York Technical College in Rock Hill, South Carolina, and Gardner-Webb University in Boiling Springs, North Carolina in the westernmost part of the Charlotte area.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] UNC Charlotte is the city's largest university.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] It is located in University City, the northeastern portion of Charlotte, which is also home to University Research Park, a 3,200 acres (13 km2) research and corporate park.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] With more than 30,000 students, UNC Charlotte is the second largest university in the state system.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Central Piedmont Community College is the largest community college in the Carolinas, with more than 70,000 students each year and 6 campuses throughout the Charlotte-Mecklenburg region.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] CPCC is part of the statewide North Carolina Community College System.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The Charlotte School of Law opened its doors in Charlotte in 2006 and was fully accredited by the American Bar Association in 2011.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The law school offered the Juris Doctor degree but the Bar association rescinded the accreditation in 2017.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte School of Law, once the largest law school in the Carolinas, has ceased to operate.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Pfeiffer University has a satellite campus in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Wake Forest University, with its main campus in Winston-Salem, North Carolina, also operates a satellite campus of its Babcock Graduate School of Management in the Uptown area.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] On March 24, 2021, it was announced Wake Forest School of Medicine would expand a 20-acre campus in Charlotte by 2024.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The Connecticut School of Broadcasting, DeVry University, and ECPI University all have branches in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The Universal Technical Institute has the NASCAR Technical Institute in nearby Mooresville, serving the Charlotte area.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Montreat College (Charlotte) maintains a School of Professional and Adult Studies in the city.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Additionally, Union Presbyterian Seminary has a non-residential campus offering the Master of Arts in Christian Education, and the Master of Divinity in Charlotte near the Beverley Woods area.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The North Carolina Research Campus, a 350-acre biotechnology hub located northeast of Charlotte in the city of Kannapolis, is a public-private venture including eight universities, one community college, the David H.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Murdock Research Institute (DHMRI), the U.S.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Department of Agriculture (USDA) and corporate entities that collaborate to advance the fields of human health, nutrition and agriculture.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The research campus is part of a larger effort by leaders in the Charlotte area to attract energy, health, and other knowledge-based industries that contribute to North Carolina's strength in biotechnology.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte has one major daily newspaper, *The Charlotte Observer*.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] It boasts the largest circulation in North Carolina and South Carolina.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte is the 24th largest radio market in the nation, according to Nielsen Audio.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] While major groups like iHeartMedia and Urban One have stations serving Charlotte, several smaller groups also own and operate stations in the area.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The local National Public Radio news affiliate is WFAE News, which sponsors a number of podcasts and radio shows.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] According to Nielsen Media Research, Charlotte is the 22nd largest television market in the nation (as of the 2016–2017 season) and the largest in the state of North Carolina.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Major television stations located in Charlotte include CBS affiliate WBTV 3 (the oldest television station in the Carolinas), ABC affiliate WSOC-TV 9, NBC affiliate WCNC-TV 36, independent station WCCB 18, and PBS member station WTVI 42.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] One cable sports network is headquartered in Charlotte: the ESPN-controlled SEC Network.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Raycom Sports is also headquartered in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Additionally, INSP is headquartered in nearby Indian Land.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] In 2020, CNN established a Charlotte bureau spearheaded by national correspondent Dianne Gallagher.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Cable television customers are served by Spectrum, which offers a localized feed of Raleigh-based Spectrum News North Carolina.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Emergency medical services for the city of Charlotte are provided by Mecklenburg EMS Agency (MEDIC).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] MEDIC received over 160,000 calls in 2022 and transported over 107,000 patients in Mecklenburg County.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The agency employs over 600 paramedics, EMTs, EMDs and admin staff.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] In addition to dispatching MEDIC's EMS calls, the agency also dispatches all county fire calls outside of the city of Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte-Mecklenburg Hospital Authority (dba Atrium Health) is the public hospital authority of Mecklenburg County.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The Charlotte Fire Department provides fire suppression, emergency medical services, public education, hazardous materials (HAZMAT) mitigation, technical rescues, and fire prevention and inspection with 1,164 personnel.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Forty-three fire stations are strategically scattered throughout Charlotte to provide a reasonable response time to emergencies in the city limits.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The Charlotte-Mecklenburg Police Department (CMPD) is a combined jurisdiction agency.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The CMPD has law enforcement jurisdiction in both the city of Charlotte and the few unincorporated areas left in Mecklenburg County.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The other small towns maintain their own law enforcement agencies for their own jurisdictions.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The department consists of approximately 1,700 sworn law enforcement officers, 550 civilian personnel, and more than 400 volunteers.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] An average of 4,939 vehicles are stolen every year in Charlotte.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] According to the Congressional Quarterly Press; '2008 City Crime Rankings: Crime in Metropolitan America,' Charlotte, North Carolina ranks as the 62nd most dangerous city larger than 75,000 inhabitants.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] However, the entire Charlotte-Gastonia Metropolitan Statistical Area ranked as 27th most dangerous out of 338 metro areas.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte has a municipal waste system consisting of trash pickup, water distribution, and waste treatment.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] There are five waste water treatment plants operated by Charlotte Water (previously Charlotte-Mecklenburg Utility Department).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Some Chester residents spoke out against the program on February 26, 2013.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte's sludge is handled, transported, and spread on farm fields in Chester by a company called Synagro, a wholly owned subsidiary of the Carlyle Group Charlotte's sludge is of the "CLASS B" variety, which means it still contains detectable levels of pathogens.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The city of Charlotte has a lower than average percentage of households without a car.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] In 2015, 7.4 percent of Charlotte households lacked a car, and decreased to 6 percent in 2016.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte averaged 1.65 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] This may be caused by Charlotte's low rankings in public transportation and walkability compared to other US cities.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The Charlotte Area Transit System (CATS) is the agency responsible for operating mass transit in the Charlotte metropolitan area, carrying over 16 million riders annually.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Established in 1999 and administered as a department of the city of Charlotte, CATS operates light rail transit, streetcar, express buses, local buses, and special bus services serving Charlotte and the surrounding area in addition to other programs such as vanpool.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] CATS' rail arm, LYNX Rapid Transit Services, comprises two lines as of fall 2020.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The Blue Line is an 18.9‑mile line north–south light rail line running through South End, Center City, NoDa, and University City.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The CityLYNX Gold Line streetcar, Phase 1 of which opened in 2015, is under Phase 2 construction as of fall 2020.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] When completed, the Gold Line will link the Beatties Ford neighborhood through Uptown and then south and east to the Elizabeth neighborhood.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The bulk of CATS ridership is derived from its extensive bus network, which has its main hub at the Charlotte Transportation Center in Uptown, which also connects to the Blue and Gold lines.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Other bus hubs are located at community transit centers in SouthPark, Eastland, and at Rosa Parks Place.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] CATS operates express buses to outlying parts of the city and some commuter bus to the northern suburbs in the Lake Norman area under the MetroRAPID umbrella.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte's central location between the population centers of the Northeast and Southeast has made it a transportation focal point and primary distribution center, with two major interstate highways, I-85 and I-77, intersecting near the city's center.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The latter highway also connects to the population centers of the Rust Belt.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte's beltway, designated I-485 and simply called "485" by local residents, was under construction for over 20 years, but funding problems slowed its progress.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The final segment was finished in mid-2015.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] I-485 has a total circumference of approximately 67 mi (108 km).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Within the city, the I-277 loop freeway encircles Charlotte's uptown (usually referred to by its two separate sections, the John Belk Freeway and the Brookshire Freeway) while Route 4 links major roads in a loop between I-277 and I-485.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Independence Freeway, which carries US 74 and links downtown with the Matthews area, is undergoing an expansion and widening in the eastern part of the city.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] In 2011, Charlotte Douglas International Airport was the sixth-busiest airport in both the U.S. and the world overall as measured by traffic (aircraft movements).
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The airport handled just over 50 million travellers in 2019, as well as many domestic and international carriers including Air Canada, Lufthansa, and Volaris.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] It is a major hub for American Airlines, having historically been a hub for its predecessors US Airways and Piedmont Airlines.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Nonstop flights are available to many destinations across the United States, Canada, Central America, the Caribbean, Europe, Mexico, and South America.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The 145th Airlift Wing of North Carolina Air National Guard is also located east of the airport.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte is served daily by three Amtrak routes with ten daily trips from a station on North Tryon Street, just outside downtown.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte is also served by both Greyhound and low-cost curbside carrier Megabus.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] Charlotte is a service stop for Greyhound routes running to Atlanta, Detroit, Jacksonville, New York and Philadelphia.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] It is also a stop for buses running out of Megabus' hub in Atlanta, with connections to Megabus' northeastern routes out of New York.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] The city is planning a new centralized downtown multimodal station called Gateway Station.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] It is expected to house Amtrak, Greyhound and the future LYNX Red Line.
[src:charlotte-north-carolina/charlotte-north-carolina-p02] It is under construction at the former site of the Greyhound station; Greyhound is currently operating from a temporary station nearby.
